text: Sunlight is essential for human health, primarily because of its role in producing vitamin D, a crucial nutrient for bone health, immune function, and even the regulation of inflammation. Research shows that regular, moderate sun exposure can improve mood, support circadian rhythms, and enhance mental clarity. Sunlight also plays a role in the production of nitric oxide, which supports cardiovascular health by helping to lower blood pressure. The modern lifestyle factors may play a more significant role. One such factor is the use of sunscreens containing chemical filters like oxybenzone, octinoxate, and avobenzone. These chemicals are absorbed by the skin and have been shown to generate free radicals and oxidative stress when exposed to UV light, potentially increasing the risk of DNA damage over time. Some studies have raised concerns about their endocrine-disrupting properties, as well. Seed oils, rich in omega-6 fatty acids, are another focus of this argument. Omega-6 fatty acids are pro-inflammatory, and a diet high in these fats can lead to increased systemic inflammation. When skin cells are inflamed, they are more susceptible to damage from UV rays. These oils also oxidize quickly under heat and UV exposure, potentially leading to cellular damage and mutations that contribute to skin cancer development. In contrast, omega-3 fatty acids (from sources like fatty fish) are anti-inflammatory and may help protect against UV damage. A return to ancestral diets rich in animal fats and an avoidance of chemical-laden products can help to support the body‚Äôs natural defenses.
